d redemption. In times of crisis, as with the one we are currently experiencing, we are faced with the dilemma of either shoring up the current political and legal order—through ever more authoritarian measures—or radically transforming it. Redemption, in the full theological sense of the word, thus implies the possibility of a new understanding of ethics and politics, aimed at creating a more just world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aDemocracyxReligious aspects. 0aPolitical theology. 0aReligion and politics. 4aPhilosophy : Continental Philosophy. 4aPolitics and Law : Law. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Theory. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion and Politics. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh1 aNewman, Saul, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2023z978311149193640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143849345940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438493459423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438493459/original  a978-3-11-149193-6  SUNY Press eBook Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles